data.enText: to run with quick short steps

data.chText: 听到他的说话声，她赶紧跑开了。
data.enText: She scuttled off when she heard the sound of his voice.

data.chText: 见一只老鼠跑过，他屏住了呼吸。
data.enText: He held his breath as a rat scuttled past.
to deliberately cause sth to fail

data.chText: 股东成功地阻止了这桩交易。

data.enText: to sink a ship deliberately by making holes in the side or bottom of it

tr: an entrance equipped with a hatch
especially a passageway between decks of a ship
shaped to permit pouring the coal onto the fire
to move about or proceed hurriedly
example: so terrified by the extraordinary ebbing of the sea that they scurried to higher ground

value.def: When people or small animals scuttle somewhere, they run there with short quick steps.

example.ex: Two very small children scuttled away in front of them...
example.tran: 两个小毛孩在他们前面屁颠屁颠地跑开了。

example.ex: Crabs scuttle along the muddy bank.
example.tran: 几只螃蟹沿着泥泞的河堤快速横行。

value.def: To scuttle a plan or a proposal means to make it fail or cause it to stop.

example.ex: Such threats could scuttle the peace conference.
example.tran: 这种威胁会阻挠和平会议。

value.def: To scuttle a ship means to sink it deliberately by making holes in the bottom.

example.ex: He personally had received orders from Commander Lehmann to scuttle the ship.
example.tran: 他个人已收到莱曼司令要求凿沉轮船的命令。

value.def: A scuttle is the same as a coal scuttle .

trans: (通常置于壁炉边的)煤斗，煤筐，煤桶
